Nuclear fear that lurked in the population after World War II ended as well as the fear of rival communities, Serbs and Albanians within the same country, all were vivid memories. The level of nationalism and the fear that increased once again made the dialogue between Serbia and Croatia more difficult. After Dayton Accords, which ended three years of armed conflict between two countries, Croatia gradually proceeded towards European integration, and Serbia engaged in European integration from the position of an official candidate. In the course of those two decades, strong political leaders have frequently engaged in rhetoric that rehabilitated the darkest chapters of bloody military confrontation. Today, many of the politicians who declared war on each other and staged a genocidal aggression, today usually gather for joint commemoration of Yugoslav dead, cutting across the ethnic lines. However, it’s hard to find an identical example in Europe where a war that descended upon two neighbouring countries with a common past would be celebrated together!

At the same time, hostile relations between the two countries aren’t as intense now as they were two decades ago, and the most significant achievement has indeed been building a brighter future, together, through the dialogue. Today, there are regions in Serbia that after the war are experiencing a decade of reconstruction and progress, and excessive politicking ceased to dominate as the main subject.
